---
/**
 * /legal/privacy — Privacy Policy.
 *
 * First-draft pre-launch privacy policy (2026-05-13). Required so the
 * platform can lawfully collect phone numbers and emails for OTP login.
 *
 * Primary regime: NZ Privacy Act 2020. Platform is global, so we also
 * acknowledge GDPR, UK GDPR, CCPA/CPRA, and the Australian Privacy Act
 * 1988 (and the APPs).
 *
 * Flagged for NZ-licensed lawyer review:
 *   - The lawful-basis mapping for each processing activity (contract /
 *     legitimate interest / consent) should be confirmed against the
 *     latest UK + EU guidance.
 *   - The 12-month post-deletion retention for fraud prevention needs a
 *     documented balancing test before launch (Article 6(1)(f) LIA).
 *   - The "approved mechanisms for NZ→US transfers under NZPA s22"
 *     wording — Tim wants a privacy lawyer to confirm we are using the
 *     right form (binding scheme rules, contractual safeguards, or a
 *     specific authorised country).
 *   - The breach-notification window (72 hours) is GDPR; NZPA requires
 *     "as soon as practicable". We meet both with 72h but a lawyer
 *     should sense-check.
 *   - All enquiries route to info@tournamental.com (single mailbox
 *     for the project; do not split into privacy@ / legal@ / hello@).
 *   - /profile/data-export page is a TODO for the identity agent.
 */
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
---
<Layout
  title="Privacy Policy · Tournamental"
  description="How Growth Spurt Ltd collects, uses, shares, and protects your personal information when you use the Tournamental platform."
  ogImage="/og/legal.png"
>
  <article
    class="container-prose pt-16 pb-20 prose-vt"
    data-cache-control="public, max-age=3600, s-maxage=86400, stale-while-revalidate=604800"
  >
    <p class="text-ink-500 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider">Legal</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mt-2">
      Privacy Policy
    </h1>
    <p class="text-ink-500 text-sm mt-3">
      Last updated: 13 May 2026. This is a pre-launch first draft pending
      review by a New Zealand licensed privacy lawyer.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-6">
      This Privacy Policy explains what personal information Tournamental
      Holdings (<strong>Tournamental</strong>, <strong>we</strong>,
      <strong>us</strong>) collects about you, why we collect it, how
      long we keep it, who we share it with, and what choices you have.
      It applies to the marketing site at <code>tournamental.com</code>,
      the play app at <code>play.tournamental.com</code>, the API at
      <code>api.tournamental.com</code>, the Telegram bot
      <code>@TournamentalBot</code>, and any other surface we operate.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Who we are and how to contact us</h2>
    <p>
      Tournamental is a subsidiary of <strong>Growth Spurt Ltd</strong>,
      a New Zealand company. Our registered office is in
      Auckland, New Zealand. You can contact us at
      <a class="link" href="mailto:info@tournamental.com">info@tournamental.com</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the purposes of the GDPR and UK GDPR, the controller of your
      personal data is Growth Spurt Ltd. We have not appointed a
      Data Protection Officer because we are not required to under
      Article 37; the privacy mailbox above is the contact point. EU
      and UK residents who need an Article 27 representative should
      contact us via the privacy mailbox and we will appoint one before
      the threshold for that requirement is met.
    </p>

    <h2>2. What we collect</h2>
    <p>
      We try to collect as little as possible. The full list is:
    </p>
    <div class="vt-privacy-table">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>What</th>
            <th>When</th>
            <th>Why</th>
            <th>Who sees it</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Phone number</td>
            <td>If you sign up with SMS or WhatsApp OTP</td>
            <td>Sending the one-time code; account recovery; fraud prevention</td>
            <td>You, us, Aiva SMS (for delivery only)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Email address</td>
            <td>If you sign up with email OTP, or you subscribe to the press / build-log feed</td>
            <td>Sending the one-time code; account recovery; transactional notifications; optional newsletters if you opt in</td>
            <td>You, us, Supabase (auth) and our email-sending sub-processor</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Handle / display name</td>
            <td>You pick one at sign-up</td>
            <td>Identifying you on leaderboards and shared brackets</td>
            <td>Public by default</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Bracket picks and cascaded summary</td>
            <td>Each time you save a pick</td>
            <td>Running the game; rendering your bracket on <code>/s/&lt;guid&gt;</code></td>
            <td>Public by default once you lock a stage</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Locked-at timestamps</td>
            <td>When you lock each pick</td>
            <td>Anti-cheat (no picks made after kick-off), audit log</td>
            <td>Public</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Approximate location (city-level)</td>
            <td>From your IP, at our edge</td>
            <td>Default tournament view, relevant affiliate routing, GDPR cookie-banner decisioning</td>
            <td>Us. Never down to street level. We do not store raw IPs after the edge resolution step.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Analytics events</td>
            <td>While you browse the site</td>
            <td>Understanding which pages work, which CTAs convert, how to improve</td>
            <td>Us via GA4 and our first-party event layer. See Cookies.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Device coarse fingerprint (user-agent + accept-language, hashed)</td>
            <td>Every request</td>
            <td>Bot detection and humanness scoring (see <a class="link" href="https://github.com/0800tim/tournamental/blob/main/docs/20-identity-and-humanness.md">doc 20</a>)</td>
            <td>Us; never the raw user-agent or raw IP</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Optional Ethereum address</td>
            <td>Only if you opt into the Drips Network contributor payout</td>
            <td>Receiving your share of platform revenue</td>
            <td>Public on chain; obviously</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      We do <strong>not</strong> collect your real name (unless you
      choose to put it in your handle), your home address, your payment
      details (we do not process payments at launch), or any biometric
      data.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Lawful basis (GDPR / UK GDPR / NZPA)</h2>
    <p>
      Under the GDPR and UK GDPR, every act of processing has a lawful
      basis. Under the NZ Privacy Act, every collection has a purpose
      tied to a function or activity of the agency. We use the bases
      below.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Contract (Article 6(1)(b)).</strong> Running your
        account, accepting your picks, delivering OTPs, showing your
        bracket on a share link — these are necessary to provide the
        service you signed up for.</li>
      <li><strong>Legitimate interest (Article 6(1)(f)).</strong>
        Server-side analytics, fraud detection, bot-net detection,
        humanness scoring, abuse investigation, security logs. The
        balancing test favours processing because the data minimisation
        (hashed device signals, no raw IPs) makes intrusion low and the
        benefit to all users high. You can object at any time at
        <a class="link" href="mailto:info@tournamental.com">info@tournamental.com</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>Consent (Article 6(1)(a)).</strong> Marketing emails
        (newsletter), GA4 and any other non-essential analytics
        cookies, cross-site advertising cookies (none on the launch
        surface), share-card auto-post to social. You can withdraw
        consent at any time without affecting the lawfulness of
        processing before withdrawal.</li>
      <li><strong>Legal obligation (Article 6(1)(c)).</strong> Where
        required, retaining records to comply with NZ or EU law,
        responding to lawful requests from public authorities.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      For New Zealand residents, the equivalent NZPA principle for each
      activity is documented in our internal Information Privacy
      Statement (available on request).
    </p>

    <h2>3a. Specific purposes for sensitive identifiers</h2>
    <p>
      Phone numbers and email addresses are the two most sensitive
      identifiers we collect because they are the keys to your
      account. We use them only for:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Delivering the one-time code that signs you in or recovers
        your account. This is the primary purpose, and it is the
        reason these identifiers are collected at all.</li>
      <li>Transactional notifications you opt in to (for example,
        "your bracket has been locked", "your syndicate result is
        in"). You can turn these off in your profile.</li>
      <li>Limited fraud prevention (see the salted-hash retention
        in section 4). We do not use your phone or email for any
        ad-targeting, lookalike audience, or upload-to-platform
        purpose.</li>
      <li>Where you give explicit consent, sending the optional
        newsletter or build-log digest. The consent is granular and
        can be withdrawn in one click.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We will never sell, rent, or trade your phone number or email
      address. We will never share them with an advertiser or
      data-broker. If law-enforcement asks us for these identifiers
      under a valid legal process, we will respond as required and,
      where the law allows, we will tell you about the request.
    </p>

    <h2>4. How long we keep it</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Phone number and email.</strong> Retained while your
        account is active. After you request deletion, we retain a
        salted hash of the identifier for 12 months for fraud
        prevention (so a banned user cannot immediately re-sign up
        with the same number) and then delete it entirely.</li>
      <li><strong>Handle.</strong> Retained as long as the account is
        active; on deletion the handle is released back to the pool
        after a 30-day quarantine.</li>
      <li><strong>Bracket picks and cascaded summary.</strong>
        Retained indefinitely under your share GUID so the share link
        keeps working. When you delete your account we anonymise the
        picks (the handle is replaced with a randomly generated alias)
        but we keep the cascade so leaderboards stay consistent. You
        can request full deletion of the cascade as well; this may
        leave gaps in historical leaderboards.</li>
      <li><strong>Approximate location and analytics events.</strong>
        Raw events: 14 months. Aggregated reporting: indefinitely.</li>
      <li><strong>Hashed device signals.</strong> 90 days.</li>
      <li><strong>Server access logs.</strong> 30 days.</li>
      <li><strong>Security incident records.</strong> As long as needed
        to manage the incident plus 7 years for audit.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>5. Sub-processors</h2>
    <p>
      We use a small set of sub-processors. Each one has a data
      processing agreement in place that meets the standard of the NZ
      Privacy Act, GDPR Article 28, and the UK GDPR equivalent.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Supabase</strong> (USA) — authentication, Postgres
        database, edge functions. Covered by the Supabase Data
        Processing Addendum and the EU Standard Contractual Clauses.</li>
      <li><strong>Cloudflare</strong> (USA, global edge) — DNS, CDN,
        tunnel, Web Application Firewall. Covered by Cloudflare's
        Binding Corporate Rules and Standard Contractual Clauses.</li>
      <li><strong>Aiva SMS</strong> (New Zealand) — SMS and WhatsApp
        one-time code delivery. Covered by a direct sub-processor
        agreement with Growth Spurt Ltd.</li>
      <li><strong>GoHighLevel</strong> (USA) — CRM for pre-launch
        syndicate signup ingestion (name, email, optional Telegram).
        Covered by GoHighLevel's DPA and EU Standard Contractual
        Clauses.</li>
      <li><strong>Google Analytics 4 / Tag Manager</strong> (Google
        Ireland Ltd / USA) — analytics. Loaded only after you accept
        analytics cookies. Server-side anonymised events are emitted
        either way (no user identifier).</li>
      <li><strong>npm and GitHub</strong> (USA) — open-source code
        hosting and package distribution. No user PII flows here.</li>
      <li><strong>Polymarket</strong> (data only) — odds data feed.
        No user PII flows.</li>
      <li><strong>StatsBomb</strong> (open data) — historical match
        event data. No user PII flows.</li>
      <li><strong>Anthropic, OpenAI, ElevenLabs</strong> (commentary
        generation only) — used to generate commentary text and audio
        from match event data. No user PII flows; we send the public
        match event stream and receive commentary back.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We will update this list before we add any new sub-processor that
      handles user personal data, and we will give 30 days' notice in
      the same way we give notice of changes to this policy.
    </p>

    <h2>6. International transfers</h2>
    <p>
      Most of our sub-processors are based in the United States. When
      your personal data is transferred from New Zealand, the European
      Economic Area, the United Kingdom, or Australia to the United
      States or any other country, we rely on the following safeguards:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>EU and UK GDPR transfers.</strong> EU Standard
        Contractual Clauses (the 2021 modules) and the UK International
        Data Transfer Addendum, with supplementary measures (encryption
        at rest, encryption in transit, access logging).</li>
      <li><strong>NZ Privacy Act 2020 transfers.</strong> Information
        Privacy Principle 12 (cross-border disclosure). We rely on
        contractual safeguards equivalent to the NZPA standard with
        each sub-processor; we do not currently rely on a country
        prescribed under section 22.</li>
      <li><strong>Australian Privacy Act transfers.</strong> APP 8
        compliant; we take reasonable steps to ensure the overseas
        recipient does not breach the APPs.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>7. Your rights</h2>
    <p>
      Depending on where you live, you have some or all of the
      following rights. We honour all of them globally because the
      Platform is global and it is simpler.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Access.</strong> Ask for a copy of the personal data
        we hold about you.</li>
      <li><strong>Rectification.</strong> Ask us to correct inaccurate
        data.</li>
      <li><strong>Deletion ("right to be forgotten").</strong> Ask us
        to delete your account and personal data, subject to the
        fraud-prevention retention in section 4.</li>
      <li><strong>Portability.</strong> Ask for your data in a
        structured, machine-readable JSON export. We will deliver
        within 30 days of a verified request.</li>
      <li><strong>Objection.</strong> Object to processing based on
        legitimate interest.</li>
      <li><strong>Withdrawal of consent.</strong> Withdraw consent for
        any consent-based processing.</li>
      <li><strong>Lodge a complaint.</strong> Complain to your local
        supervisory authority. New Zealand: the Office of the Privacy
        Commissioner (<a class="link" href="https://www.privacy.org.nz/">privacy.org.nz</a>).
        EU: your local data protection authority. UK: the ICO.
        Australia: the OAIC.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>8. How to exercise your rights</h2>
    <p>
      The fastest route is the in-product data-export and deletion
      page in your profile (under construction, will live at
      <code>/profile/data-export</code>).
      {/* TODO: wire up by the identity agent before launch. */}
      Until that is live, email
      <a class="link" href="mailto:info@tournamental.com">info@tournamental.com</a>
      with the phone number or email on your account, and the right
      you want to exercise. We will respond within 30 days. If we need
      more time (where allowed by law) we will tell you why.
    </p>
    <p>
      To prevent identity theft we may need to verify that the request
      is genuinely from you. We will do this by sending a one-time
      code to the contact on file, never by asking for any other
      personal information.
    </p>

    <h2>8a. Automated decision-making</h2>
    <p>
      We use automated decisions in two places:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Humanness scoring.</strong> The identity service
        (see <a class="link" href="https://github.com/0800tim/tournamental/blob/main/docs/20-identity-and-humanness.md">doc 20</a>)
        scores each account against a set of bot-detection signals
        (hashed device fingerprint, request timing, picks pattern). A
        low score does not, by itself, ban the account; it changes
        the friction (extra OTP confirmations, rate-limit
        adjustments, hidden from the global leaderboard).</li>
      <li><strong>Cookie-banner decisioning.</strong> Whether the
        cookie banner appears, and what categories it offers by
        default, depends on your inferred region (see section 2).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      You can ask for a human review of any automated decision that
      materially affects you (for example, a leaderboard suppression
      or a rate-limit lockout) by emailing
      <a class="link" href="mailto:info@tournamental.com">info@tournamental.com</a>.
      We will review within 30 days.
    </p>

    <h2>8b. California (CCPA / CPRA) specifics</h2>
    <p>
      If you are a California resident, the categories of personal
      information we collect (per CCPA Section 1798.140) map to:
      identifiers (your phone number, email, handle, account ID),
      internet activity (analytics events, page views, click events),
      and inferences drawn from those identifiers (humanness score,
      preferred tournament view). We do not "sell" personal
      information for money. We may share device-graph signals with
      our humanness-score sub-processor for the limited purpose of
      bot detection; you can opt out via the cookie preference centre
      under "Performance and analytics". Verifiable consumer requests
      go to <a class="link" href="mailto:info@tournamental.com">info@tournamental.com</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>9. Children</h2>
    <p>
      The Platform is intended for users aged 13 and over (or older if
      your local law requires; see section 4 of the Terms of Service).
      We do not knowingly collect personal data from anyone below the
      applicable age. If you believe a child below that age has signed
      up, please contact us and we will delete the account.
    </p>

    <h2>9a. How we handle minor sign-ups in error</h2>
    <p>
      If we receive a credible report that a user is below the
      applicable minimum age (see section 9), we will suspend the
      account pending review and contact the user (or their
      verifiable parent or guardian, where available) before taking
      any further action. If the report is confirmed, we will delete
      the account and all associated data within seven days, except
      where a legal hold applies. We will not retain the underlying
      identifier (phone or email) in our salted-hash fraud-prevention
      store for accounts deleted on this ground, because the harm
      from a banned-handle re-signup is lower than the harm from
      keeping any record of a minor's contact.
    </p>

    <h2>10. Security</h2>
    <p>
      We take security seriously. In short:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>All data at rest in our Postgres database is encrypted by
        Supabase using AES-256.</li>
      <li>All data in transit uses TLS 1.2 or higher, terminated at
        Cloudflare and re-encrypted to origin.</li>
      <li>OTP attempts are rate-limited per phone number, per IP, and
        per device fingerprint. Failed attempts are logged.</li>
      <li>Privileged access to production systems is multi-factor
        authenticated and logged.</li>
      <li>We run automated dependency scanning on every pull request.</li>
      <li>Responsible disclosures are welcome at
        <a class="link" href="mailto:security@tournamental.com">security@tournamental.com</a>;
        see <a class="link" href="https://github.com/0800tim/tournamental/blob/main/SECURITY.md">SECURITY.md</a>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      No system is perfectly secure. If you spot something, please tell
      us.
    </p>

    <h2>10a. Open source and operational transparency</h2>
    <p>
      Because the Platform code is open source under Apache 2.0, you
      can inspect exactly how we handle your data. The auth flow lives
      in <code>apps/auth-sms/</code>, the identity scoring in
      <code>apps/identity/</code>, the analytics pipeline in
      <code>packages/analytics/</code>, and the database schema in
      <code>infra/db/</code>. We publish session notes for every
      contributor session under
      <code>sessions/&lt;date&gt;_&lt;agent&gt;_&lt;task&gt;.md</code>,
      so the changes to any of these systems are auditable in real
      time. If you want a tour, ask at
      <a class="link" href="mailto:info@tournamental.com">info@tournamental.com</a>
      and we will point a privacy researcher at the relevant files.
    </p>

    <h2>11. Breach notification</h2>
    <p>
      If we suffer a personal-data breach that is likely to result in
      serious harm or a risk to your rights and freedoms, we will
      notify the Office of the Privacy Commissioner (and, where
      applicable, the relevant EU and UK supervisory authorities)
      within 72 hours of becoming aware of it, and we will notify you
      directly without undue delay.
    </p>

    <h2>12. Cookies</h2>
    <p>
      We use a small number of cookies and similar technologies. The
      details — what each cookie does, how long it lives, and how to
      opt out — are in our separate
      <a class="link" href="/legal/cookies">Cookie Notice</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>13. Changes to this policy</h2>
    <p>
      We may update this policy from time to time. For a material
      change we will give at least 30 days' notice via email and an
      on-site banner. The "Last updated" date at the top of the page
      reflects the most recent change.
    </p>

    <h2>14. Contact for complaints</h2>
    <p>
      If you have a complaint about how we handle your personal data,
      please tell us first at
      <a class="link" href="mailto:info@tournamental.com">info@tournamental.com</a>.
      We will acknowledge within five working days and respond
      substantively within 30 days.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you are not satisfied with our response, you have the right
      to complain to your local data-protection authority:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>New Zealand residents:</strong> Office of the
        Privacy Commissioner (<a class="link" href="https://www.privacy.org.nz/">privacy.org.nz</a>).</li>
      <li><strong>EU residents:</strong> your local supervisory
        authority, listed at
        <a class="link" href="https://edpb.europa.eu/about-edpb/about-edpb/members_en">edpb.europa.eu</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>UK residents:</strong> Information Commissioner's
        Office (<a class="link" href="https://ico.org.uk/">ico.org.uk</a>).</li>
      <li><strong>Australian residents:</strong> Office of the
        Australian Information Commissioner (<a class="link" href="https://www.oaic.gov.au/">oaic.gov.au</a>).</li>
      <li><strong>California residents:</strong> California Attorney
        General (<a class="link" href="https://oag.ca.gov/">oag.ca.gov</a>);
        see also the "Your California Privacy Rights" section of
        our forthcoming CCPA notice.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr class="my-10 border-ink-700/70" />

    <p class="text-ink-500 text-sm">
      Companion documents:
      <a class="link" href="/legal/terms">Terms of Service</a>
      ·
      <a class="link" href="/legal/cookies">Cookie Notice</a>
      ·
      <a class="link" href="/legal">Legal hub</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* The privacy table is the densest text on the site and lives on a
     360px viewport. Stack to cards on narrow screens; show as a real
     table from ~700px up. Reuses the prose-vt colour tokens so it
     follows the light/dark theme switcher. */
  .vt-privacy-table {
    margin: 1.6rem 0;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }
  .vt-privacy-table table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
  .vt-privacy-table th,
  .vt-privacy-table td {
    text-align: left;
    vertical-align: top;
    padding: 0.7rem 0.6rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--vt-border);
  }
  .vt-privacy-table th {
    color: var(--vt-fg-strong);
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .vt-privacy-table td {
    color: var(--vt-fg-muted);
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .vt-privacy-table table,
    .vt-privacy-table thead,
    .vt-privacy-table tbody,
    .vt-privacy-table tr,
    .vt-privacy-table th,
    .vt-privacy-table td {
      display: block;
      width: 100%;
    }
    .vt-privacy-table thead {
      display: none;
    }
    .vt-privacy-table tr {
      margin-bottom: 1.1rem;
      border: 1px solid var(--vt-border);
      border-radius: 0.6rem;
      padding: 0.4rem 0.6rem;
    }
    .vt-privacy-table td {
      border-bottom: none;
      padding: 0.35rem 0;
    }
    .vt-privacy-table td::before {
      content: attr(data-label);
      display: block;
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      color: var(--vt-fg-strong);
      margin-bottom: 0.1rem;
    }
  }
</style>
